```suggestion
@[simps!]
noncomputable def functorHomEquiv [HasFunctorEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚] [HasEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚] :
    (Fâ‚ âŸ¶ Fâ‚‚) â‰ƒ (ðŸ™_ (J â¥¤ V) âŸ¶ functorEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚) :=
  (homEquiv V).trans (isLimitConeFunctorEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚).homEquiv

lemma functorHomEquiv_id [HasFunctorEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚] [HasEnrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚] :
    (functorHomEquiv V) (ðŸ™ Fâ‚) = functorEnrichedId V Fâ‚ := by
  aesop_cat
```
Thanks! (I have kept only the `apply_app` lemma, as the other one is not very useful.)

```suggestion
  dsimp
  rw [homEquiv_comp]
```

Should work with the `simps!` attribute on `functorHomEquiv`

I'm happy with the answer "No, this is an unreasonable ask", but:

Could I request that whenever we introduce an `erw`, we *also* include a comment explaining either why it is unavoidable, or better than alternatives?

Optimistically, this will result in some `erw` not happening, as writing the note might inspire a solution.

And otherwise, it means that we won't have to come back to the same `erw` again and again and work out the explanation before forgetting it again.

It seems at this `erw` that the problem is that before the `erw` the composition
```
end_.lift (fun x â†¦ enrichedHomÏ€ V (Under.forget j â‹™ Fâ‚) (Under.forget j â‹™ Fâ‚) ((Under.map f).obj x)) â‹¯ â‰«
      end_.Ï€ (diagram V (Under.forget j' â‹™ Fâ‚) (Under.forget j' â‹™ Fâ‚)) k
```
is "badly typed", with the target of the first morphism being 
```
end_ (diagram V (Under.map f â‹™ Under.forget j â‹™ Fâ‚) (Under.map f â‹™ Under.forget j â‹™ Fâ‚))
```
and the source of the second morphism being
```
end_ (diagram V (Under.forget j' â‹™ Fâ‚) (Under.forget j' â‹™ Fâ‚))
```

So maybe there is some defeq in `functorEnrichedHom` that could be lifted to an explicit `eqToHom`? I better move on to other things now, sorry.

Perhaps there is a missing piece of tooling here, however. What about a `#check_comp` tactic that looks for all morphism compositions and reports when sources and targets don't match (at reducible+instances transparency). (Or even more generally, a `#check_implicits`.) I'm not saying that any report from this would be a problem, but it might be helpful in identifying what is going on in problems like this.

I have managed to remove all `erw` by introducing `precompEnrichedHom'` which is a variant of `enrichedHom V Fâ‚ Fâ‚‚ âŸ¶ enrichedHom V (G â‹™ Fâ‚) (G â‹™ Fâ‚‚)` but with `G â‹™ Fâ‚` and `G â‹™ Fâ‚‚` replaced by isomorphic functors. I expected it would complicate things, but eventually automation works better...
